<p class="lead">When you're starting a Michigan business, insurance can feel like one more cost before you've made a dollar. But the right coverage is what keeps one lawsuit, fire, or injury from ending the business before it gets going — and you don't need everything on day one. Here's what you actually need, what's required, and what can wait.</p>

<h2>What Michigan legally requires</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong><a href="../../business/workers-compensation/">Workers' compensation</a></strong> — required for almost every Michigan employer with employees (generally 1+ working 35+ hours/week, or 3+ at any time). This one isn't optional once you hire.</li>
  <li><strong>Commercial auto</strong> — if the business owns vehicles, Michigan No-Fault and registration require coverage. Even using your personal vehicle for the business can require <a href="../../business/commercial-auto-insurance/">commercial auto</a>.</li>
</ul>
<p>Most other coverages aren't mandated by the state — but they're effectively required by the people you do business with.</p>

<h2>What your clients, landlord, and lender will require</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong><a href="../../business/general-liability-insurance/">General liability</a></strong> — the moment you sign a commercial lease, bid a job, or take on a client, you'll be asked for proof of it (often $1M/$2M limits, with the other party named as additional insured). It's the foundation policy.</li>
  <li><strong><a href="../../business/professional-liability-insurance/">Professional liability (E&amp;O)</a></strong> — if you give advice or deliver a professional service, clients increasingly require it before they'll sign.</li>
  <li><strong>Commercial property</strong> — if you own or lease space, equipment, or inventory, you'll need to cover it (and your lease likely requires it).</li>
</ul>

<h2>The smart starter stack for most new Michigan businesses</h2>
<p>For a lot of small businesses, the most cost-effective starting point is a <strong><a href="../../business/business-owners-policy/">Business Owner's Policy (BOP)</a></strong> — it bundles general liability and commercial property (and business income) into one policy for 10–20% less than buying them separately. From there you add:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Workers' comp as soon as you hire.</li>
  <li>Commercial auto if you have business vehicles.</li>
  <li><a href="../../business/cyber-liability-insurance/">Cyber liability</a> if you handle customer data (most businesses do).</li>
  <li>Professional liability if you advise or provide a service.</li>
</ul>

<h2>What can wait — and what can't</h2>
<p>You can scale into umbrella limits, surety bonds, and specialized coverages as the business grows and contracts demand them. What you <em>can't</em> wait on is the gap that gets you sued or shut down: general liability before your first client or lease, and workers' comp before your first employee's first shift. Going uninsured on those, even briefly, is the risk that ends new businesses.</p>

